  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "ugnIjCRItMXv0+zKnfFgAZMbfWI=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Claim\n\nA **Single Owner Chunk (SOC)** is a chunk whose address is derived from an identifier and an owner Ethereum address, giving every account a private virtual namespace of writable chunk slots.\n\n## Evidence\n\n- Address formula: `Keccak256(identifier || owner_address)` \u2014 deterministic from a 32-byte identifier and the owner's Ethereum address\n- Content layout: 32-byte identifier + 65-byte signature (r, s, v) + span + payload\n- Only the private-key holder can sign updates; anyone can read\n- A SOC can **wrap** a CAC \u2014 the SOC payload becomes the CAC's span + data\n- The addressing scheme means each account controls what lives at each identifier \u2014 the primitive underneath feeds and GSOC\n\n## Why it matters\n\nSOCs are the primitive that turns Swarm from immutable content storage into a system that supports mutable, signed state. Feeds and GSOC are both built on top of SOCs.\n",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z"
    }
  },
